 L2.11681846,21.1592049 C1.6216514,21.3645957 1.3386988,21.4848244 1.3386988,21.4848244 L2.13491427,24.7226518 L3.11702303,24.4821943 C3.43123203,24.4020417 3.8145341,24.3085305 4.25047853,24.1966509 C4.69629339,24.1131588 5.17171957,23.8843901 5.70143317,23.6756596 C6.2229214,23.436872 6.82995345,23.2782368 7.39256851,22.8958425 C7.95847373,22.5318166 8.61156782,22.227905 9.18734348,21.7403106 C9.74502332,21.2376875 10.4178583,20.8018583 10.9146704,20.1639779 C11.4575446,19.5661738 11.9938385,18.9383125 12.4100421,18.2236193 C12.8920485,17.542323 13.2194181,16.7942329 13.5648835,16.0544921 C13.8774474,15.3147512 14.1291436,14.5583119 14.3347778,13.8235806 C14.7246602,12.3507783 14.8990379,10.9514491 14.966486,9.75417102 C15.0224184,8.5552231 14.989517,7.55832629 14.9204239,6.83695372 C14.8958606,6.53687434 14.8607433,6.23778152 14.8151392,5.94024755 L14.8151392,5.94024755 Z\">\n            </path>\n          </g>\n        </g>\n      </g>\n    </svg>\n  </div>\n  \n  <figcaption class=\"quote-long-container__name\">Harriet Kater, climate lead (Australia), Australasian Centre for Corporate Responsibility</figcaption>\n</figure>\n\n    \n  \n	\n\n\n  \n  \n    <div class=\"general-text\">\n	<p><strong>Policy impacts</strong></p>\n<p>The Labor government&rsquo;s update to the NDC under the Paris Agreement represents a shift in Australia&rsquo;s political attitude towards climate change. Australia has had a policy in place since 2016 that sets emissions baselines for sites that emit 100,000 tCO2-e per annum. But according to Harriet Kater, climate lead (Australia) at the Australasian Centre for Corporate Responsibility, this was &ldquo;entirely ineffective&rdquo; under the previous government. </p>\n<p>The new Labor government plans to decrease those baselines to incentivise emissions reductions. These baselines and decline pathways are yet to be determined.</p>\n<p>Large Australian companies like metals and mining group BHP will be affected by the government&rsquo;s updated policy, as Kater explains: &ldquo;The primary Labor government policy that will affect carbon-intensive resource companies like BHP is the safeguard mechanism.&rdquo;</p>\n<p>Introduced in 2014, the safeguard mechanism is intended to manage Australia&rsquo;s biggest polluters, which in total emit 140 million tonnes of greenhouse gas emissions &ndash; or just shy of 30% of Australia&rsquo;s total, according to the <a href=\"https://www.climatecouncil.org.au/resources/what-is-the-safeguard-mechanism/\">Climate Council</a> think tank. For future regulatory changes, the intention is for the safeguard mechanism baselines to ratchet down to 2030. </p>\n<p>Kater says: &ldquo;Having enjoyed a long period without any form of carbon regulation, the lobbying from companies and their industry association will be frenetic as the baselines are established.&rdquo;</p>\n<p>One feature of the new policy is the acceptance of Australian carbon credit units (ACCUs) as abatement. According to Kater, this is concerning since Australia&rsquo;s carbon market has recently been rocked by major integrity concerns. &ldquo;A challenge for Labor is its ongoing commitment to new oil, gas, and coal production and the impact this will have on Australia&rsquo;s emissions&rsquo; reduction trajectory, along with our chances of a stable climate,&rdquo; Kater adds.</p>\n<p><strong>Investor responses</strong></p>\n<p>Guidance around 2030 and 2050 targets are set to enable investors to make better decisions. Kater suggests that considering Australia&rsquo;s improved but still modest 2030 target and the risks surrounding the Safeguard Mechanism, investors should maintain pressure on companies to set science-based emission reduction targets for Scopes 1, 2 and 3.</p>\n<p>Investors need new non-traditional financial information relevant to how climate change affects firms&rsquo; long-term performance to make intelligent long-term investment decisions, according to Rebecca Healey, co-chair of the EMEA regional and EMEA regulatory subcommittees at the <a href=\"https://www.fixtrading.org/\">FIX Trading Community</a>.</p>\n<p>Healey explains the best way of providing investors with the transparency and comparability they need for their decisions, will be to get existing standards into the asset management community.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;This does not necessarily have to be individual rating agencies scoring but about whether the company in question has got sufficient information on Scope 1, 2 and 3,&rdquo; she adds.</p>\n<p>According to Kater, investors in Australia should closely monitor the conduct of companies and their industry associations as they engage with the policy development process to ensure its integrity is not eroded beyond repair. </p>\n</div>\n    \n  \n	\n\n\n  \n</div>\n\n        \n        \n        <div class=\"uppercase font-avenir-bold text-14px\">\n          <span class=\"font-avenir-black\">Content Tags:</span>\n          <a class=\"underline text-primary-dark hover:text-primary\" href=\"https://www.netzeroinvestor.net/category/australasia\">Australasia</a>&nbsp; \n        </div>\n\n        \n        \n        <div class=\"social-media-share\" x-cloak x-data=\"socialWidget\">\n\n    <button class=\"social-media-share__share-button\" title=\"Share content\">\n        <div class=\"social-media-share__share-button-inner\">\n            <span class=\"social-media-share__share-button-text\">Share</span>\n            <i class=\"\">\n                <svg class=\"w-18 h-16 \" viewbox=\"0 0 21 18\" version=\"1.1\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\">\n                    <title>Open Share Menu</title>\n                    <g stroke=\"none\" stroke-width=\"1\" fill=\"none\" fill-rule=\"evenodd\">\n                        <g transform=\"translate(-56.000000, -7.000000)\" stroke=\"#383B41\" stroke-width=\"2\">\n                            <g transform=\"translate(57.000000, 8.000000)\">\n                          